eeminence as US Secretary of State, that mentality remained throughout his life as evinces in his personal attitudes and professional conduct.Relational rights, identified and termed here for the first time by Hoffer, are communal and reciprocal, what everyone owed to every other member of the community. It is a jurisprudential outlook that arises directly from living in a village. Though limited by the Victorian mores and the racialist presumptions of his day, the concept of relational rights that animated Seward was the natural antithesis to the theories and practices of slavery. In the legal regime underpinning the peculiar institution, masters owed nothing to their bondmen and women, while those enslaved unconditionally owed life and labor to their masters. The irrepressible conflict was, for Seward, jurisprudential as well as moral and political.Hoffer's leading assumption in Seward's Law is that a lifetime spent as a lawyer influences how a person responds to the challenges of everyday life. Seward remained a country lawyer at heart and that fact defined the course of his political career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCountry lawyerszNew York (State)vBiography. 0aPractice of lawxPolitical aspectszNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aLEGAL HISTORY & STUDIES. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh  aseward folly, william henry seward litigator, lawyers in the civil war era, antebellum politics, law and slavery in the civil war era.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOO